# Airlock

**Stop watching your agent.** A local-first safety envelope that lets you run coding
agents unattended — detection by **provenance and dataflow**, not keywords.

Airlock makes **zero network calls of its own** and pulls in **zero runtime dependencies**.
Standard library only.

## Why keyword guardrails fail

A lexical gate greps a command for scary words. Reword the command, base64-wrap the
payload, or split the string and you walk right past it. Airlock does not read words.
It tracks *where bytes came from* and *where they are going*.

## The moat (`airlock.core.taint`)

- **Provenance** — every tool *result* is tagged trusted (operator/host) or untrusted
  (web / email / file / MCP). Unknown sources are untrusted by construction (fail-closed).
- **Taint** — reading untrusted content taints the session.
- **Escalation** — a high-risk action within a short window of untrusted content has its
  severity raised. "Read a webpage, then tried to POST somewhere" is the shape of a
  prompt-injection exploit.
- **Egress matching** — when a secret is read, its bytes are fingerprinted with a rolling
  hash (Rabin-Karp shingles) plus base64/hex variants. When a later action's outbound
  payload contains those bytes — reworded, wrapped, or partial — the overlap is detected.
  You cannot reword (or base64) your way past a hash comparison.
- **Taint graph** — every escalation / egress hit records an edge, emitted into the audit log.

## Verdict tiers

| severity | verdict |
|----------|---------|
| low | allow + log |
| medium | notify |
| high | block until approved |
| tainted egress / irreversible | block, show the taint graph |

**Promise #4:** irreversible actions (money movement, destructive ops, publishing/sending)
**always hard-stop for a human**, no matter what the policy says.

## Install

```sh
pip install .
```

Requires Python 3.9+.

## Usage

Phase 1 ships one command — `airlock report` — **read-only, zero-config**. It replays a
Claude Code session / hook log (JSONL) through the policy engine and prints what the agent
has been doing. It cannot block, cannot break anything, and sends nothing anywhere.

```sh
airlock report                       # replays the bundled sample session
airlock report --log path/to/log.jsonl
```

The log adapter is deliberately forgiving: logs vary across Claude Code versions, hooks,
and SDKs, so a malformed line is **skipped and counted, never crashed on** — a security
tool that dies on bad input hands control straight back to the agent.

Later phases (`run`, `digest`, `eval`) are intentionally not advertised until they ship.

## Development

```sh
python3 -m pytest -q
```

Everything in `airlock.engine` and `airlock.core` is pure and does no I/O — the ruling on
an action is deterministic and testable without a network, a disk, or a real agent.

